# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: convex-hull-trick
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In geometry, the **convex hull**, **convex envelope** or **convex closure** of a shape is the smallest convex set that contains it.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull may be defined either as the intersection of all convex sets containing a given subset of a Euclidean space, or equivalently as the set of all convex combinations of points in the subset.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For a bounded subset of the plane, the convex hull may be visualized as the shape enclosed by a rubber band stretched around the subset.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Convex hulls of open sets are open, and convex hulls of compact sets are compact.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Every compact convex set is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull operator is an example of a closure operator, and every antimatroid can be represented by applying this closure operator to finite sets of points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The algorithmic problems of finding the convex hull of a finite set of points in the plane or other low-dimensional Euclidean spaces, and its dual problem of intersecting half-spaces, are fundamental problems of computational geometry.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] They can be solved in time $O(n\log n)$ for two or three dimensional point sets, and in time matching the worst-case output complexity given by the upper bound theorem in higher dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] As well as for finite point sets, convex hulls have also been studied for simple polygons, Brownian motion, space curves, and epigraphs of functions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Convex hulls have wide applications in mathematics, statistics, combinatorial optimization, economics, geometric modeling, and ethology.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Related structures include the orthogonal convex hull, convex layers, Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram, and convex skull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] A set of points in a Euclidean space is defined to be convex if it contains the line segments connecting each pair of its points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For bounded sets in the Euclidean plane, not all on one line, the boundary of the convex hull is the simple closed curve with minimum perimeter containing X .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] One may imagine stretching a rubber band so that it surrounds the entire set S and then releasing it, allowing it to contract; when it becomes taut, it encloses the convex hull of S .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] This formulation does not immediately generalize to higher dimensions: for a finite set of points in three-dimensional space, a neighborhood of a spanning tree of the points encloses them with arbitrarily small surface area, smaller than the surface area of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, in higher dimensions, variants of the obstacle problem of finding a minimum-energy surface above a given shape can have the convex hull as their solution.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For objects in three dimensions, the first definition states that the convex hull is the smallest possible convex bounding volume of the objects.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] It is not obvious that the first definition makes sense: why should there exist a unique minimal convex set containing X , for every X ?
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, the second definition, the intersection of all convex sets containing X , is well-defined.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] It is a subset of every other convex set Y that contains X , because Y is included among the sets being intersected.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Thus, it is exactly the unique minimal convex set containing X .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Therefore, the first two definitions are equivalent.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Each convex set containing X must (by the assumption that it is convex) contain all convex combinations of points in X , so the set of all convex combinations is contained in the intersection of all convex sets containing X .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Conversely, the set of all convex combinations is itself a convex set containing X , so it also contains the intersection of all convex sets containing X , and therefore the second and third definitions are equivalent.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In fact, according to Carathéodory's theorem, if X is a subset of a d -dimensional Euclidean space, every convex combination of finitely many points from X is also a convex combination of at most $d+1$ points in X .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The set of convex combinations of a $(d+1)$ -tuple of points is a simplex; in the plane it is a triangle and in three-dimensional space it is a tetrahedron.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Therefore, every convex combination of points of X belongs to a simplex whose vertices belong to X , and the third and fourth definitions are equivalent.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In two dimensions, the convex hull is sometimes partitioned into two parts, the upper hull and the lower hull, stretching between the leftmost and rightmost points of the hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] More generally, for convex hulls in any dimension, one can partition the boundary of the hull into upward-facing points (points for which an upward ray is disjoint from the hull), downward-facing points, and extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For three-dimensional hulls, the upward-facing and downward-facing parts of the boundary form topological disks.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The *closed convex hull* of a set is the closure of the convex hull, and the *open convex hull* is the interior (or in some sources the relative interior) of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The closed convex hull of X is the intersection of all closed half-spaces containing X .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] If the convex hull of X is already a closed set itself (as happens, for instance, if X is a finite set or more generally a compact set), then it equals the closed convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, an intersection of closed half-spaces is itself closed, so when a convex hull is not closed it cannot be represented in this way.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] If the open convex hull of a set X is d -dimensional, then every point of the hull belongs to an open convex hull of at most $2d$ points of X .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The sets of vertices of a square, regular octahedron, or higher-dimensional cross-polytope provide examples where exactly $2d$ points are needed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Topologically, the convex hull of an open set is always itself open, and (in Euclidean spaces) the convex hull of a compact set is always itself compact.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, there exist closed sets for which the convex hull is not closed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] (the set of points that lie on or above the witch of Agnesi) has the open upper half-plane as its convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Convex hulls can be defined more generally in infinite-dimensional topological vector spaces, but they may not preserve compactness in these spaces.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Instead, the compactness of convex hulls of compact sets, in finite-dimensional Euclidean spaces, is generalized by the Krein–Smulian theorem, according to which the closed convex hull of a weakly compact subset of a Banach space (a subset that is compact under the weak topology) is weakly compact.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] An extreme point of a convex set is a point in the set that does not lie on any open line segment between any other two points of the same set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For a convex hull, every extreme point must be part of the given set, because otherwise it cannot be formed as a convex combination of given points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] According to the Krein–Milman theorem, every compact convex set in a Euclidean space (or more generally in a locally convex topological vector space) is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, this may not be true for convex sets that are not compact; for instance, the whole Euclidean plane and the open unit ball are both convex, but neither one has any extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Choquet theory extends this theory from finite convex combinations of extreme points to infinite combinations (integrals) in more general spaces.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] When applied to a finite set of points, this is the closure operator of an antimatroid, the shelling antimatroid of the point set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Every antimatroid can be represented in this way by convex hulls of points in a Euclidean space of high-enough dimension.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The operations of constructing the convex hull and taking the Minkowski sum commute with each other, in the sense that the Minkowski sum of convex hulls of sets gives the same result as the convex hull of the Minkowski sum of the same sets.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] This provides a step towards the Shapley–Folkman theorem bounding the distance of a Minkowski sum from its convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The projective dual operation to constructing the convex hull of a set of points is constructing the intersection of a family of closed halfspaces that all contain the origin (or any other designated point).
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull of a finite point set $S\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ forms a convex polygon when $d=2$ , or more generally a convex polytope in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Each extreme point of the hull is called a vertex, and (by the Krein–Milman theorem) every convex polytope is the convex hull of its vertices.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] It is the unique convex polytope whose vertices belong to S and that encloses all of S .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For sets of points in general position, the convex hull is a simplicial polytope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] According to the upper bound theorem, the number of faces of the convex hull of n points in d -dimensional Euclidean space is $O(n^{\lfloor d/2\rfloor })$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In particular, in two and three dimensions the number of faces is at most linear in n .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull of a simple polygon encloses the given polygon and is partitioned by it into regions, one of which is the polygon itself.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The other regions, bounded by a polygonal chain of the polygon and a single convex hull edge, are called *pockets*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Computing the same decomposition recursively for each pocket forms a hierarchical description of a given polygon called its *convex differences tree*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Reflecting a pocket across its convex hull edge expands the given simple polygon into a polygon with the same perimeter and larger area, and the Erdős–Nagy theorem states that this expansion process eventually terminates.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The curve generated by Brownian motion in the plane, at any fixed time, has probability 1 of having a convex hull whose boundary forms a continuously differentiable curve.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, for any angle $\theta$ in the range $\pi /2<\theta <\pi$ , there will be times during the Brownian motion where the moving particle touches the boundary of the convex hull at a point of angle $\theta$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The Hausdorff dimension of this set of exceptional times is (with high probability) $1-\pi /2\theta$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For the convex hull of a space curve or finite set of space curves in general position in three-dimensional space, the parts of the boundary away from the curves are developable and ruled surfaces.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull or lower convex envelope of a function f on a real vector space is the function whose epigraph is the lower convex hull of the epigraph of f .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] It is the unique maximal convex function majorized by f .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The definition can be extended to the convex hull of a set of functions (obtained from the convex hull of the union of their epigraphs, or equivalently from their pointwise minimum) and, in this form, is dual to the convex conjugate operation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In computational geometry, a number of algorithms are known for computing the convex hull for a finite set of points and for other geometric objects.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Computing the convex hull means constructing an unambiguous, efficient representation of the required convex shape.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Output representations that have been considered for convex hulls of point sets include a list of linear inequalities describing the facets of the hull, an undirected graph of facets and their adjacencies, or the full face lattice of the hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In two dimensions, it may suffice more simply to list the points that are vertices, in their cyclic order around the hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For convex hulls in two or three dimensions, the complexity of the corresponding algorithms is usually estimated in terms of n , the number of input points, and h , the number of points on the convex hull, which may be significantly smaller than n .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For higher-dimensional hulls, the number of faces of other dimensions may also come into the analysis.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Graham scan can compute the convex hull of n points in the plane in time $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For points in two and three dimensions, more complicated output-sensitive algorithms are known that compute the convex hull in time $O(n\log h)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] These include Chan's algorithm and the Kirkpatrick–Seidel algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] For dimensions $d>3$ , the time for computing the convex hull is $O(n^{\lfloor d/2\rfloor })$ , matching the worst-case output complexity of the problem.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull of a simple polygon in the plane can be constructed in linear time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Dynamic convex hull data structures can be used to keep track of the convex hull of a set of points undergoing insertions and deletions of points, and kinetic convex hull structures can keep track of the convex hull for points moving continuously.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The construction of convex hulls also serves as a tool, a building block for a number of other computational-geometric algorithms such as the rotating calipers method for computing the width and diameter of a point set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Several other shapes can be defined from a set of points in a similar way to the convex hull, as the minimal superset with some property, the intersection of all shapes containing the points from a given family of shapes, or the union of all combinations of points for a certain type of combination.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Each of alpha shape is the union of some of the features of the Delaunay triangulation, selected by comparing their circumradius to the parameter alpha.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The point set itself forms one endpoint of this family of shapes, and its convex hull forms the other endpoint.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex layers of a point set are a nested family of convex polygons, the outermost of which is the convex hull, with the inner layers constructed recursively from the points that are not vertices of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex skull of a polygon is the largest convex polygon contained inside it.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] It can be found in polynomial time, but the exponent of the algorithm is high.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Convex hulls have wide applications in many fields.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Within mathematics, convex hulls are used to study polynomials, matrix eigenvalues, and unitary elements, and several theorems in discrete geometry involve convex hulls.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] They are used in robust statistics as the outermost contour of Tukey depth, are part of the bagplot visualization of two-dimensional data, and define risk sets of randomized decision rules.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Convex hulls of indicator vectors of solutions to combinatorial problems are central to combinatorial optimization and polyhedral combinatorics.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In economics, convex hulls can be used to apply methods of convexity in economics to non-convex markets.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In geometric modeling, the convex hull property Bézier curves helps find their crossings, and convex hulls are part of the measurement of boat hulls.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] And in the study of animal behavior, convex hulls are used in a standard definition of the home range.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Newton polygons of univariate polynomials and Newton polytopes of multivariate polynomials are convex hulls of points derived from the exponents of the terms in the polynomial, and can be used to analyze the asymptotic behavior of the polynomial and the valuations of its roots.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Convex hulls and polynomials also come together in the Gauss–Lucas theorem, according to which the roots of the derivative of a polynomial all lie within the convex hull of the roots of the polynomial.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In spectral analysis, the numerical range of a normal matrix is the convex hull of its eigenvalues.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The Russo–Dye theorem describes the convex hulls of unitary elements in a C*-algebra.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In discrete geometry, both Radon's theorem and Tverberg's theorem concern the existence of partitions of point sets into subsets with intersecting convex hulls.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The definitions of a convex set as containing line segments between its points, and of a convex hull as the intersection of all convex supersets, apply to hyperbolic spaces as well as to Euclidean spaces.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] However, in hyperbolic space, it is also possible to consider the convex hulls of sets of ideal points, points that do not belong to the hyperbolic space itself but lie on the boundary of a model of that space.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The boundaries of convex hulls of ideal points of three-dimensional hyperbolic space are analogous to ruled surfaces in Euclidean space, and their metric properties play an important role in the geometrization conjecture in low-dimensional topology.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Hyperbolic convex hulls have also been used as part of the calculation of canonical triangulations of hyperbolic manifolds, and applied to determine the equivalence of knots.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] See also the section on Brownian motion for the application of convex hulls to this subject, and the section on space curves for their application to the theory of developable surfaces.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In robust statistics, the convex hull provides one of the key components of a bagplot, a method for visualizing the spread of two-dimensional sample points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The contours of Tukey depth form a nested family of convex sets, with the convex hull outermost, and the bagplot also displays another polygon from this nested family, the contour of 50% depth.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In statistical decision theory, the risk set of a randomized decision rule is the convex hull of the risk points of its underlying deterministic decision rules.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In combinatorial optimization and polyhedral combinatorics, central objects of study are the convex hulls of indicator vectors of solutions to a combinatorial problem.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] If the facets of these polytopes can be found, describing the polytopes as intersections of halfspaces, then algorithms based on linear programming can be used to find optimal solutions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In multi-objective optimization, a different type of convex hull is also used, the convex hull of the weight vectors of solutions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] One can maximize any quasiconvex combination of weights by finding and checking each convex hull vertex, often more efficiently than checking all possible solutions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In the Arrow–Debreu model of general economic equilibrium, agents are assumed to have convex budget sets and convex preferences.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] These assumptions of convexity in economics can be used to prove the existence of an equilibrium.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] When actual economic data is non-convex, it can be made convex by taking convex hulls.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The Shapley–Folkman theorem can be used to show that, for large markets, this approximation is accurate, and leads to a "quasi-equilibrium" for the original non-convex market.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In geometric modeling, one of the key properties of a Bézier curve is that it lies within the convex hull of its control points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] This so-called "convex hull property" can be used, for instance, in quickly detecting intersections of these curves.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In the geometry of boat and ship design, chain girth is a measurement of the size of a sailing vessel, defined using the convex hull of a cross-section of the hull of the vessel.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] It differs from the skin girth, the perimeter of the cross-section itself, except for boats and ships that have a convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The convex hull is commonly known as the minimum convex polygon in ethology, the study of animal behavior, where it is a classic, though perhaps simplistic, approach in estimating an animal's home range based on points where the animal has been observed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In quantum physics, the state space of any quantum system — the set of all ways the system can be prepared — is a convex hull whose extreme points are positive-semidefinite operators known as pure states and whose interior points are called mixed states.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The Schrödinger–HJW theorem proves that any mixed state can in fact be written as a convex combination of pure states in multiple ways.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] A convex hull in thermodynamics was identified by Josiah Willard Gibbs (1873), although the paper was published before the convex hull was so named.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] In a set of energies of several stoichiometries of a material, only those measurements on the lower convex hull will be stable.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] When removing a point from the hull and then calculating its distance to the hull, its distance to the new hull represents the degree of stability of the phase.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The lower convex hull of points in the plane appears, in the form of a Newton polygon, in a letter from Isaac Newton to Henry Oldenburg in 1676.
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] The term "convex hull" itself appears as early as the work of Garrett Birkhoff (1935), and the corresponding term in German appears earlier, for instance in Hans Rademacher's review of Kőnig (1922).
[src:convex-hull-trick/convex-hull] Other terms, such as "convex envelope", were also used in this time frame.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In both contexts it refers to simplifying a complicated problem by breaking it down into simpler sub-problems in a recursive manner.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] While some decision problems cannot be taken apart this way, decisions that span several points in time do often break apart recursively.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Likewise, in computer science, if a problem can be solved optimally by breaking it into sub-problems and then recursively finding the optimal solutions to the sub-problems, then it is said to have *optimal substructure*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If sub-problems can be nested recursively inside larger problems, so that dynamic programming methods are applicable, then there is a relation between the value of the larger problem and the values of the sub-problems.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In the optimization literature this relationship is called the Bellman equation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In terms of mathematical optimization, dynamic programming usually refers to simplifying a decision by breaking it down into a sequence of decision steps over time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This is done by defining a sequence of **value functions** *V*1, *V*2, ..., *V**n* taking *y* as an argument representing the **state** of the system at times *i* from 1 to *n*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The definition of *V**n*(*y*) is the value obtained in state *y* at the last time *n*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The values *V**i* at earlier times *i* = *n* −1, *n* − 2, ..., 2, 1 can be found by working backwards, using a recursive relationship called the Bellman equation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] For *i* = 2, ..., *n*, *V**i*−1 at any state *y* is calculated from *V**i* by maximizing a simple function (usually the sum) of the gain from a decision at time *i* − 1 and the function *V**i* at the new state of the system if this decision is made.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Since *V**i* has already been calculated for the needed states, the above operation yields *V**i*−1 for those states.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Finally, *V*1 at the initial state of the system is the value of the optimal solution.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The optimal values of the decision variables can be recovered, one by one, by tracking back the calculations already performed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The solution to this problem is an optimal control law or policy $\mathbf {u} ^{\ast }=h(\mathbf {x} (t),t)$ , which produces an optimal trajectory $\mathbf {x} ^{\ast }$ and a cost-to-go function $J^{\ast }$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In practice, this generally requires numerical techniques for some discrete approximation to the exact optimization relationship.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] at the k -th stage of n equally spaced discrete time intervals, and where ${\hat {f}}$ and ${\hat {\mathbf {g} }}$ denote discrete approximations to f and $\mathbf {g}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This functional equation is known as the Bellman equation, which can be solved for an exact solution of the discrete approximation of the optimization equation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In economics, the objective is generally to maximize (rather than minimize) some dynamic social welfare function.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In Ramsey's problem, this function relates amounts of consumption to levels of utility.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Loosely speaking, the planner faces the trade-off between contemporaneous consumption and future consumption (via investment in capital stock that is used in production), known as intertemporal choice.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Future consumption is discounted at a constant rate $\beta \in (0,1)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] where c is consumption, k is capital, and f is a production function satisfying the Inada conditions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] An initial capital stock $k_{0}>0$ is assumed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let $c_{t}$ be consumption in period t, and assume consumption yields utility $u(c_{t})=\ln(c_{t})$ as long as the consumer lives.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Assume the consumer is impatient, so that he discounts future utility by a factor b each period, where $0<b<1$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Assume initial capital is a given amount $k_{0}>0$ , and suppose that this period's capital and consumption determine next period's capital as $k_{t+1}=Ak_{t}^{a}-c_{t}$ , where A is a positive constant and $0<a<1$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Written this way, the problem looks complicated, because it involves solving for all the choice variables $c_{0},c_{1},c_{2},\ldots ,c_{T}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming approach to solve this problem involves breaking it apart into a sequence of smaller decisions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] To do so, we define a sequence of *value functions* $V_{t}(k)$ , for $t=0,1,2,\ldots ,T,T+1$ which represent the value of having any amount of capital k at each time t.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] There is (by assumption) no utility from having capital after death, $V_{T+1}(k)=0$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The value of any quantity of capital at any previous time can be calculated by backward induction using the Bellman equation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This problem is much simpler than the one we wrote down before, because it involves only two decision variables, $c_{t}$ and $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Intuitively, instead of choosing his whole lifetime plan at birth, the consumer can take things one step at a time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] At time t, his current capital $k_{t}$ is given, and he only needs to choose current consumption $c_{t}$ and saving $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] To actually solve this problem, we work backwards.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] For simplicity, the current level of capital is denoted as k. $V_{T+1}(k)$ is already known, so using the Bellman equation once we can calculate $V_{T}(k)$ , and so on until we get to $V_{0}(k)$ , which is the *value* of the initial decision problem for the whole lifetime.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] We see that it is optimal to consume a larger fraction of current wealth as one gets older, finally consuming all remaining wealth in period T, the last period of life.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] There are two key attributes that a problem must have in order for dynamic programming to be applicable: optimal substructure and overlapping sub-problems.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If a problem can be solved by combining optimal solutions to *non-overlapping* sub-problems, the strategy is called "divide and conquer" instead.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This is why merge sort and quick sort are not classified as dynamic programming problems.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Some programming languages can automatically memoize the result of a function call with a particular set of arguments, in order to speed up call-by-name evaluation (this mechanism is referred to as *call-by-need*).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Some languages make it possible portably (e.g.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Some languages have automatic memoization built in, such as tabled Prolog and J, which supports memoization with the *M.* adverb.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In any case, this is only possible for a referentially transparent function.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Memoization is also encountered as an easily accessible design pattern within term-rewrite based languages such as Wolfram Language.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming is widely used in bioinformatics for tasks such as sequence alignment, protein folding, RNA structure prediction and protein-DNA binding.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The first dynamic programming algorithms for protein-DNA binding were developed in the 1970s independently by Charles DeLisi in the US and by Georgii Gurskii and Alexander Zasedatelev in the Soviet Union.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Recently these algorithms have become very popular in bioinformatics and computational biology, particularly in the studies of nucleosome positioning and transcription factor binding.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm for the shortest path problem is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's famous Principle of Optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Using dynamic programming in the calculation of the *n*th member of the Fibonacci sequence improves its performance greatly.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In particular, `fib(2)` was calculated three times from scratch.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In larger examples, many more values of `fib`, or *subproblems*, are recalculated, leading to an exponential time algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Now, suppose we have a simple map object, *m*, which maps each value of `fib` that has already been calculated to its result, and we modify our function to use it and update it.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This technique of saving values that have already been calculated is called *memoization*; this is the top-down approach, since we first break the problem into subproblems and then calculate and store values.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In the **bottom-up** approach, we calculate the smaller values of `fib` first, then build larger values from them.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This method also uses O(*n*) time since it contains a loop that repeats n − 1 times, but it only takes constant (O(1)) space, in contrast to the top-down approach which requires O(*n*) space to store the map.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In both examples, we only calculate `fib(2)` one time, and then use it to calculate both `fib(4)` and `fib(3)`, instead of computing it every time either of them is evaluated.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Consider the problem of assigning values, either zero or one, to the positions of an *n* × *n* matrix, with *n* even, so that each row and each column contains exactly *n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] We ask how many different assignments there are for a given n.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] There are at least three possible approaches: brute force, backtracking, and dynamic programming.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Brute force consists of checking all assignments of zeros and ones and counting those that have balanced rows and columns (*n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] As there are $2^{n^{2}}$ possible assignments and ${\tbinom {n}{n/2}}^{n}$ sensible assignments, this strategy is not practical for arbitrarily large values of n .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Backtracking for this problem consists of choosing some order of the matrix elements and recursively placing ones or zeros, while checking that in every row and column the number of elements that have not been assigned plus the number of ones or zeros are both at least *n* / 2.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] While more sophisticated than brute force, this approach will visit every solution once, making it impractical for *n* larger than six, since the number of solutions is already 116963796250 for *n* = 8, as we shall see.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming makes it possible to count the number of solutions without visiting them all.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Imagine backtracking values for the first row – what information would we require about the remaining rows, in order to be able to accurately count the solutions obtained for each first row value?
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] We consider *k* × *n* boards, where 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*, whose k rows contain $n/2$ zeros and $n/2$ ones.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The function *f* to which memoization is applied maps vectors of *n* pairs of integers to the number of admissible boards (solutions).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] There is one pair for each column, and its two components indicate respectively the number of zeros and ones that have yet to be placed in that column.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If any one of the results is negative, then the assignment is invalid and does not contribute to the set of solutions (recursion stops).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Otherwise, we have an assignment for the top row of the *k* × *n* board and recursively compute the number of solutions to the remaining (*k* − 1) × *n* board, adding the numbers of solutions for every admissible assignment of the top row and returning the sum, which is being memoized.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The base case is the trivial subproblem, which occurs for a 1 × *n* board.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The number of solutions for this board is either zero or one, depending on whether the vector is a permutation of *n* / 2 (0, 1) and *n* / 2 (1, 0) pairs or not.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Links to the MAPLE implementation of the dynamic programming approach may be found among the external links.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Consider a checkerboard with *n* × *n* squares and a cost function `c(i, j)` which returns a cost associated with square `(i,j)` (`*i*` being the row, `*j*` being the column).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This problem exhibits **optimal substructure**.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] That is, the solution to the entire problem relies on solutions to subproblems.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Starting at rank `n` and descending to rank `1`, we compute the value of this function for all the squares at each successive rank.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Picking the square that holds the minimum value at each rank gives us the shortest path between rank `n` and rank `1`.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The function `q(i, j)` is equal to the minimum cost to get to any of the three squares below it (since those are the only squares that can reach it) plus `c(i, j)`.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The first line of this equation deals with a board modeled as squares indexed on `1` at the lowest bound and `n` at the highest bound.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The second line specifies what happens at the first rank; providing a base case.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The third line, the recursion, is the important part.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] It represents the `A,B,C,D` terms in the example.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] From this definition we can derive straightforward recursive code for `q(i, j)`.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This function only computes the path cost, not the actual path.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This, like the Fibonacci-numbers example, is horribly slow because it too exhibits the **overlapping sub-problems** attribute.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] That is, it recomputes the same path costs over and over.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] However, we can compute it much faster in a bottom-up fashion if we store path costs in a two-dimensional array `q[i, j]` rather than using a function.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This avoids recomputation; all the values needed for array `q[i, j]` are computed ahead of time only once.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Precomputed values for `(i,j)` are simply looked up whenever needed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] We also need to know what the actual shortest path is.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] To do this, we use another array `p[i, j]`; a *predecessor array*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This array records the path to any square `s`.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The predecessor of `s` is modeled as an offset relative to the index (in `q[i, j]`) of the precomputed path cost of `s`.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] To reconstruct the complete path, we lookup the predecessor of `s`, then the predecessor of that square, then the predecessor of that square, and so on recursively, until we reach the starting square.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Now the rest is a simple matter of finding the minimum and printing it.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In genetics, sequence alignment is an important application where dynamic programming is essential.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Typically, the problem consists of transforming one sequence into another using edit operations that replace, insert, or remove an element.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Each operation has an associated cost, and the goal is to find the sequence of edits with the lowest total cost.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] 3. replacing the first character of A with the first character of B, and performing optimal alignments of the tails of A and B.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The partial alignments can be tabulated in a matrix, where cell (i,j) contains the cost of the optimal alignment of A[1..i] to B[1..j].
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The cost in cell (i,j) can be calculated by adding the cost of the relevant operations to the cost of its neighboring cells, and selecting the optimum.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Different variants exist, see Smith–Waterman algorithm and Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The **Tower of Hanoi** or **Towers of Hanoi** is a mathematical game or puzzle.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] S(n, h, t) := solution to a problem consisting of n disks that are to be moved from rod h to rod t.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] For n=1 the problem is trivial, namely S(1,h,t) = "move a disk from rod h to rod t" (there is only one disk left).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The number of moves required by this solution is 2*n* − 1.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If the objective is to **maximize** the number of moves (without cycling) then the dynamic programming functional equation is slightly more complicated and 3*n* − 1 moves are required.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] A famous puzzle relates to dropping eggs from a building to determine at which height they start to break.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] terminology, in which the first floor is at ground level).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If only one egg is available and we wish to be sure of obtaining the right result, the experiment can be carried out in only one way.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Drop the egg from the first-floor window; if it survives, drop it from the second-floor window.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] In the worst case, this method may require 36 droppings.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] What is the lowest number of egg-droppings that is guaranteed to work in all cases?
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] For instance, *s* = (2,6) indicates that two test eggs are available and 6 (consecutive) floors are yet to be tested.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The initial state of the process is *s* = (*N*,*H*) where *N* denotes the number of test eggs available at the commencement of the experiment.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The process terminates either when there are no more test eggs (*n* = 0) or when *k* = 0, whichever occurs first.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If termination occurs at state *s* = (0,*k*) and *k* > 0, then the test failed.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] It is easy to solve this equation iteratively by systematically increasing the values of *n* and *k*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Notice that the above solution takes $O(nk^{2})$ time with a DP solution.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This can be improved to $O(nk\log k)$ time by binary searching on the optimal x in the above recurrence, since $W(n-1,x-1)$ is increasing in x while $W(n,k-x)$ is decreasing in x , thus a local minimum of $\max(W(n-1,x-1),W(n,k-x))$ is a global minimum.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Also, by storing the optimal x for each cell in the DP table and referring to its value for the previous cell, the optimal x for each cell can be found in constant time, improving it to $O(nk)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let k be the total number of floors such that the eggs break when dropped from the k th floor (The example above is equivalent to taking $k=37$ ).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let m be the minimum floor from which the egg must be dropped to be broken.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let $f(t,n)$ be the maximum number of values of m that are distinguishable using t tries and n eggs.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let a be the floor from which the first egg is dropped in the optimal strategy.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If the first egg broke, m is from 1 to a and distinguishable using at most $t-1$ tries and $n-1$ eggs.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If the first egg did not break, m is from $a+1$ to k and distinguishable using $t-1$ tries and n eggs.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Then the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum x such that $f(x,n)\geq k$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] To do so, we could compute $\{f(t,i):0\leq i\leq n\}$ in order of increasing t , which would take $O(nx)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Thus, if we separately handle the case of $n=1$ , the algorithm would take $O(n{\sqrt {k}})$ time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] But the recurrence relation can in fact be solved, giving $f(t,n)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}{\binom {t}{i}}$ , which can be computed in $O(n)$ time using the identity ${\binom {t}{i+1}}={\binom {t}{i}}{\frac {t-i}{i+1}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Since $f(t,n)\leq f(t+1,n)$ for all $t\geq 0$ , we can binary search on t to find x , giving an $O(n\log k)$ algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:convex-hull-trick/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In geometry, an **envelope** of a planar family of curves is a curve that is tangent to each member of the family at some point, and these points of tangency together form the whole envelope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Classically, a point on the envelope can be thought of as the intersection of two "infinitesimally adjacent" curves, meaning the limit of intersections of nearby curves.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] This idea can be generalized to an envelope of surfaces in space, and so on to higher dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] To have an envelope, it is necessary that the individual members of the family of curves are differentiable curves as the concept of tangency does not apply otherwise, and there has to be a smooth transition proceeding through the members.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] But these conditions are not sufficient – a given family may fail to have an envelope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] A simple example of this is given by a family of concentric circles of expanding radius.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Let each curve $C_{t}$ in the family be given as the solution of an equation $f_{t}(x,y)=0$ (see implicit curve), where t is a parameter.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Write $F(t,x,y)=f_{t}(x,y)$ and assume F is differentiable.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] for some value of t , where $\partial F/\partial t$ is the partial derivative of F with respect to t .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Letting $u\to t$ gives the definition above.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] An important special case is when $F(t,x,y)$ is a polynomial in t .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] This includes, by clearing denominators, the case where $F(t,x,y)$ is a rational function in t .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In this case, the definition amounts to t being a double root of $F(t,x,y)$ , so the equation of the envelope can be found by setting the discriminant of F to 0 (because the definition demands $F=0$ at some t and first derivative $F=0$ i.e. its value 0 and it is min/max at that t ).
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] For example, let $C_{t}$ be the line whose x and y intercepts are t and $11-t$ , this is shown in the animation above.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Often when F is not a rational function of the parameter it may be reduced to this case by an appropriate substitution.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The envelope $E_{2}$ is a curve tangent to all of the $C_{t}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The envelope $E_{3}$ is the boundary of the region filled by the curves $C_{t}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Then $E_{1}\subseteq {\mathcal {D}}$ , $E_{2}\subseteq {\mathcal {D}}$ and $E_{3}\subseteq {\mathcal {D}}$ , where ${\mathcal {D}}$ is the set of points defined at the beginning of this subsection's parent section.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] These definitions $E_{1}$ , $E_{2}$ , and $E_{3}$ of the envelope may be different sets.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Consider for instance the curve $y=x^{3}$ parametrised by ${\displaystyle \gamma$ where $\gamma (t)=(t,t^{3})$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The one-parameter family of curves will be given by the tangent lines to $\gamma$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] First we calculate the discriminant ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Calculating the partial derivative $F_{t}=6t(x-t)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Next, assuming that $t=0$ and substituting into F gives $F(0,(x,y))=-y$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] So, assuming $t=0$ , it follows that $F=F_{t}=0$ if and only if $y=0$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] One curve is given by $F(t,(x,y))=0$ and a nearby curve is given by $F(t+\varepsilon ,(x,y))=0$ where $\varepsilon$ is some very small number.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The intersection point comes from looking at the limit of $F(t,(x,y))=F(t+\varepsilon ,(x,y))$ as $\varepsilon$ tends to zero.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] If $t\neq 0$ then L has only a single factor of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The y value is calculated by knowing that this point must lie on a tangent line to the original curve $\gamma$ : that $F(t,(x,y))=0$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Substituting and solving gives $y=t^{3}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] When $t=0$ , L is divisible by $\varepsilon ^{2}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The curve itself is the curve that is tangent to all of its own tangent lines.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Every point in the plane has at least one tangent line to $\gamma$ passing through it, and so region filled by the tangent lines is the whole plane.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The boundary $E_{3}$ is therefore the empty set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Indeed, consider a point in the plane, say $(x_{0},y_{0})$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] This is a cubic in t and as such has at least one real solution.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] It follows that at least one tangent line to $\gamma$ must pass through any given point in the plane.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] If $y>x^{3}$ and $y>0$ then each point $(x,y)$ has exactly one tangent line to $\gamma$ passing through it.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] If $y<x^{3}$ and $y>0$ then each point $(x,y)$ has exactly three distinct tangent lines to $\gamma$ passing through it.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] If $y=x^{3}$ and $y\neq 0$ then each point $(x,y)$ has exactly two tangent lines to $\gamma$ passing through it (this corresponds to the cubic having one ordinary root and one repeated root).
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The same is true if $y\neq x^{3}$ and $y=0$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] If $y=x^{3}$ and $x=0$ , i.e., $x=y=0$ , then this point has a single tangent line to $\gamma$ passing through it (this corresponds to the cubic having one real root of multiplicity 3).
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In string art it is common to cross-connect two lines of equally spaced pins.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] For simplicity, set the pins on the x - and y -axes; a non-orthogonal layout is a rotation and scaling away.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] A general straight-line thread connects the two points $(0,k-t)$ and $(t,0)$ , where k is an arbitrary scaling constant, and the family of lines is generated by varying the parameter t .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] From simple geometry, the equation of this straight line is $y=-(k-t)x/t+k-t$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] These two equations jointly define the equation of the envelope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] We can take a rotation of the axes where the b axis is the line $y=x$ oriented northeast and the a axis is the line $y=-x$ oriented southeast.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] which is apparently the equation for a parabola with axis along $a=0$ , or $y=x$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Let $I\subset \mathbb {R}$ be an open interval and let $\gamma :I\to \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ be a smooth plane curve parametrised by arc length.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Consider the one-parameter family of normal lines to $\gamma (I)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] A line is normal to $\gamma$ at $\gamma (t)$ if it passes through $\gamma (t)$ and is perpendicular to the tangent vector to $\gamma$ at $\gamma (t)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Let $\mathbf {T}$ denote the unit tangent vector to $\gamma$ and let $\mathbf {N}$ denote the unit normal vector.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Clearly $(x-y)\cdot \mathbf {T} =0$ if and only if $x-\gamma$ is perpendicular to $\mathbf {T}$ , or equivalently, if and only if $x-\gamma$ is parallel to $\mathbf {N}$ , or equivalently, if and only if $x=\gamma +\lambda \mathbf {N}$ for some λ ∈ **R**.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] is exactly the normal line to $\gamma$ at $\gamma (t_{0})$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] where $\kappa$ is the plane curve curvature of $\gamma$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] It has been seen that $F=0$ if and only if $x-\gamma =\lambda \mathbf {N}$ for some $\lambda \in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] This is exactly the evolute of the curve $\gamma$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The following example shows that in some cases the envelope of a family of curves may be seen as the topologic boundary of a union of sets, whose boundaries are the curves of the envelope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] To write a Cartesian representation for $\textstyle \Delta _{\alpha }$ , start with any $\textstyle s>0$ , $\textstyle t>0$ satisfying $\textstyle s^{\alpha }+t^{\alpha }=1$ and any $\textstyle (x,y)\in \mathbb {R} _{+}^{2}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Notice that, in particular, the value $\alpha =1$ gives the arc of parabola of the Example 2, and the value $\alpha =2$ (meaning that all hypotenuses are unit length segments) gives the astroid.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] We consider the following example of envelope in motion.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Suppose at initial height 0 , one casts a projectile into the air with constant initial velocity v but different elevation angles $\theta$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Let x be the horizontal axis in the motion surface, and let y denote the vertical axis.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Here t denotes motion time, $\theta$ is elevation angle, g denotes gravitational acceleration, and v is the constant initial speed (not velocity).
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Clearly the resulted envelope is also a concave parabola.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] For example, the tangent planes to a surface along a curve in the surface form such a family.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] This curve is called the **characteristic** of the family at a .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] As a varies the locus of these characteristic curves defines a surface called the **envelope** of the family of surfaces.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The idea of an envelope of a family of smooth submanifolds follows naturally.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In general, if we have a family of submanifolds with codimension c then we need to have at least a c -parameter family of such submanifolds.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] For example: a one-parameter family of curves in three-space ( $c=2$ ) does not, generically, have an envelope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Envelopes are connected to the study of ordinary differential equations (ODEs), and in particular singular solutions of ODEs.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Consider, for example, the one-parameter family of tangent lines to the parabola $y=x^{2}$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] These are given by the generating family $F(t,(x,y))=t^{2}-2tx+y$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The zero level set $F(t_{0},(x,y))=0$ gives the equation of the tangent line to the parabola at the point $(t_{0},t_{0}^{2})$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Not surprisingly $y=2tx-t^{2}$ are all solutions to this ODE.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] However, the envelope of this one-parameter family of lines, which is the parabola $y=x^{2}$ , is also a solution to this ODE.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Another famous example is Clairaut's equation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Envelopes can be used to construct more complicated solutions of first order partial differential equations (PDEs) from simpler ones.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Let $F(x,u,\nabla u)=0$ be a first order PDE, where x is a variable with values in an open set $\Omega \subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , u is an unknown real-valued function, $\nabla u$ is the gradient of u , and F is a continuously differentiable function that is regular in $\nabla u$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Suppose that $u(x;a)$ is an m -parameter family of solutions: that is, for each fixed $a\in A\subset \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , $u(x;a)$ is a solution of the differential equation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] for $a=\varphi (x)$ as a function of x .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] and also solves the differential equation (provided that it exists as a continuously differentiable function).
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Geometrically, the graph of $v(x)$ is everywhere tangent to the graph of some member of the family $u(x;a)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Since the differential equation is first order, it only puts a condition on the tangent plane to the graph, so that any function everywhere tangent to a solution must also be a solution.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The same idea underlies the solution of a first order equation as an integral of the Monge cone.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The Monge cone is a cone field in the $\mathbb {R} ^{n+1}$ of the $(x,u)$ variables cut out by the envelope of the tangent spaces to the first order PDE at each point.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] A solution of the PDE is then an envelope of the cone field.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In Riemannian geometry, if a smooth family of geodesics through a point P in a Riemannian manifold has an envelope, then P has a conjugate point where any geodesic of the family intersects the envelope.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The same is true more generally in the calculus of variations: if a family of extremals to a functional through a given point P has an envelope, then a point where an extremal intersects the envelope is a conjugate point to P .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In geometrical optics, a caustic is the envelope of a family of light rays.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] In this picture there is an arc of a circle.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The light rays (shown in blue) are coming from a source *at infinity*, and so arrive parallel.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] When they hit the circular arc the light rays are scattered in different directions according to the law of reflection.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] When a light ray hits the arc at a point the light will be reflected as though it had been reflected by the arc's tangent line at that point.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The reflected light rays give a one-parameter family of lines in the plane.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The envelope of these lines is the reflective caustic.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] A reflective caustic will generically consist of smooth points and ordinary cusp points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] among smooth curves $\gamma$ on $[a,b]$ with fixed endpoints $\gamma (a)$ and $\gamma (b)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The caustic determined by a given point P (in the image the point is at infinity) is the set of conjugate points to P .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Light may pass through anisotropic inhomogeneous media at different rates depending on the direction and starting position of a light ray.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] The boundary of the set of points to which light can travel from a given point q after a time t is known as the wave front after time t , denoted here by $\Phi _{q}(t)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] It consists of precisely the points that can be reached from q in time t by travelling at the speed of light.
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] Huygens's principle asserts that the wave front set $\Phi _{q_{0}}\!(s+t)$ is the envelope of the family of wave fronts $\Phi _{q}(s)$ for $q\in \Phi _{q_{0}}(t)$ .
[src:convex-hull-trick/envelope-mathematics] More generally, the point $q_{0}$ could be replaced by any curve, surface or closed set in space.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] In mathematical optimization, **linear-fractional programming** (**LFP**) is a generalization of linear programming (LP).
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Whereas the objective function in a linear program is a linear function, the objective function in a linear-fractional program is a ratio of two linear functions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] A linear program can be regarded as a special case of a linear-fractional program in which the denominator is the constant function 1.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] The constraints have to restrict the feasible region to $\{\mathbf {x} |\mathbf {d} ^{T}\mathbf {x} +\beta >0\}$ , i.e. the region on which the denominator is positive.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Alternatively, the denominator of the objective function has to be strictly negative in the entire feasible region.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Both linear programming and linear-fractional programming represent optimization problems using linear equations and linear inequalities, which for each problem-instance define a feasible set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Fractional linear programs have a richer set of objective functions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Informally, linear programming computes a policy delivering the best outcome, such as maximum profit or lowest cost.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] In contrast, a linear-fractional programming is used to achieve the highest *ratio* of outcome to cost, the ratio representing the highest efficiency.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] For example, in the context of LP we maximize the objective function **profit = income − cost** and might obtain maximum profit of $100 (= $1100 of income − $1000 of cost).
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Using LFP we might obtain an efficiency of $10/$50 = 0.2 with a profit of only $10, but only requiring $50 of investment.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Any linear-fractional program can be transformed into a linear program, assuming that the feasible region is non-empty and bounded, using the **Charnes–Cooper transformation**.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] The main idea is to introduce a new non-negative variable t to the program which will be used to rescale the constants involved in the program ( $\alpha ,\beta ,\mathbf {b}$ ).
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] This allows us to require that the denominator of the objective function ( $\mathbf {d} ^{T}\mathbf {x} +\beta$ ) equals 1.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Let the dual variables associated with the constraints $A\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {b} t\leq \mathbf {0}$ and $\mathbf {d} ^{T}\mathbf {y} +\beta t-1=0$ be denoted by $\mathbf {u}$ and $\lambda$ , respectively.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] which is an LP and which coincides with the dual of the equivalent linear program resulting from the Charnes–Cooper transformation.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] The objective function in a linear-fractional problem is both quasiconcave and quasiconvex (hence quasilinear) with a monotone property, pseudoconvexity, which is a stronger property than quasiconvexity.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] A linear-fractional objective function is both pseudoconvex and pseudoconcave, hence pseudolinear.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Since an LFP can be transformed to an LP, it can be solved using any LP solution method, such as the simplex algorithm (of George B.
[src:convex-hull-trick/linear-fractional-programming] Dantzig), the criss-cross algorithm, or interior-point methods.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] In mathematics, the **lower envelope** or **pointwise minimum** of a finite set of functions is the pointwise minimum of the functions, the function whose value at every point is the minimum of the values of the functions in the given set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] The concept of a lower envelope can also be extended to partial functions by taking the minimum only among functions that have values at the point.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] The **upper envelope** or **pointwise maximum** is defined symmetrically.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] For an infinite set of functions, the same notions may be defined using the infimum in place of the minimum, and the supremum in place of the maximum.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] For continuous functions from a given class, the lower or upper envelope is a piecewise function whose pieces are from the same class.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] For convex functions or quasiconvex functions, the upper envelope is again convex or quasiconvex.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] The lower envelope is not, but can be replaced by the lower convex envelope to obtain an operation analogous to the lower envelope that maintains convexity.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] The upper and lower envelopes of Lipschitz functions preserve the property of being Lipschitz.
[src:convex-hull-trick/lower-envelope] However, the lower and upper envelope operations do not necessarily preserve the property of being a continuous function.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] In geometry, a polygon P in the plane is called **monotone** with respect to a straight line L, if every line orthogonal to L intersects the boundary of P at most twice.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Similarly, a polygonal chain C is called **monotone** with respect to a straight line L, if every line orthogonal to L intersects C at most once.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] For many practical purposes this definition may be extended to allow cases when some edges of P are orthogonal to L, and a simple polygon may be called monotone if a line segment that connects two points in P and is orthogonal to L lies completely in P.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Following the terminology for monotone functions, the former definition describes **polygons strictly monotone** with respect to L.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Assume that *L* coincides with the *x*-axis.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Then the leftmost and rightmost vertices of a monotone polygon decompose its boundary into two monotone polygonal chains such that when the vertices of any chain are being traversed in their natural order, their X-coordinates are monotonically increasing or decreasing.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] In fact, this property may be taken for the definition of monotone polygon and it gives the polygon its name.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A convex polygon is monotone with respect to any straight line and a polygon which is monotone with respect to every straight line is convex.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A linear time algorithm is known to report all directions in which a given simple polygon is monotone.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Point in polygon queries with respect to a monotone polygon may be answered in logarithmic time after linear time preprocessing (to find the leftmost and rightmost vertices).
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A monotone polygon may be easily triangulated in linear time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] For a given set of points in the plane, a bitonic tour is a monotone polygon that connects the points.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] The minimum perimeter bitonic tour for a given point set with respect to a fixed direction may be found in polynomial time using dynamic programming.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] It is easily shown that such a minimal bitonic tour is a simple polygon: a pair of crossing edges may be replaced with a shorter non-crossing pair while preserving the bitonicity of the new tour.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A simple polygon may be easily cut into monotone polygons in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] However, since a triangle is a monotone polygon, polygon triangulation is in fact cutting a polygon into monotone ones, and it may be performed for simple polygons in *O*(*n*) time with a complex algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A simpler randomized algorithm with linear expected time is also known.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Cutting a simple polygon into the minimal number of uniformly monotone polygons (i.e., monotone with respect to the same line) can be performed in polynomial time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] In the context of motion planning, two nonintersecting monotone polygons are separable by a single translation (i.e., there exists a translation of one polygon such that the two become separated by a straight line into different halfplanes) and this separation may be found in linear time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A polygon is called **sweepable**, if a straight line may be continuously moved over the whole polygon in such a way that at any moment its intersection with the polygonal area is a convex set.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A monotone polygon is sweepable by a line which does not change its orientation during the sweep.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A polygon is **strictly sweepable** if no portion of its area is swept more than once.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Both types of sweepability are recognized in quadratic time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] There is no single straightforward generalization of polygon monotonicity to higher dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] In one approach the preserved monotonicity trait is the line *L*.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] A three-dimensional polyhedron is called **weakly monotonic** in direction *L* if all cross-sections orthogonal to *L* are simple polygons.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] If the cross-sections are convex, then the polyhedron is called **weakly monotonic in convex sense**.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] Both types may be recognized in polynomial time.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] In another approach the preserved one-dimensional trait is the orthogonal direction.
[src:convex-hull-trick/monotone-polygon] This gives rise for the notion of polyhedral terrain in three dimensions: a polyhedral surface with the property that each vertical (i.e., parallel to Z axis) line intersects the surface at most by one point or segment.
